Today's intro reminded me of a conversation I had with some co-workers just last week. We were discussing giving our boss a massage coupon for her birthday and since I knew she went to yoga practice, I suggested something that would help her energy. The answer I got was "She's doing powerful rocket yoga, I don't think energy matters." 
And it made me so sad. So sad because I've come to the mat to find a place of calm and peace. Or breath and energy flowing like one. Yes, my body is changing, but that's a consequence of my practice not the sole focus of it. And to imagine people going to their mat just for the body-related goals makes me think they're missing so much more... It's just sad, in a way

Including projects I've been working on, trying new things, talking to more people, getting out more, being with my family, etc. And it got bad. But I came back to do it again, and I don't feel as stressed to do it perfectly. I feel better now, and I think I learned something from quitting this episode briefly. It sounds ridiculous; I'm pretty sure this episode has exposed a part of me I left undealt with though. I wasn't disciplined, and I didn't want to fail. So after Day 17 of True being the worst yoga day ever for me, both physically and mentally ,and after having to sit out a day because after days 16 and 17 I had really wrenched my lower back and could barely bend over.., Day 18 has been somewhat of an epiphany (or surrender) for me.  I took my frustration and anger (yes it was full blown anger) after Day 17 and my day off to do some research into Yoga and atheism and how to connect the two   .  I also spent some time watching some videos of plus size gals like myself doing yoga and how they handled getting into those poses I just can't seem to get to.   First of all I realized, I don't have to be spiritual to do yoga.  When you start into the meditation speak or talk of the 3rd eye, I know it's okay to turn that off in my head and think of things that are meaningful to me instead.  For example, at the end of todays practice when you went to the third eye, I took my hands straight up over my head pointed toward the sky, in honor of the star stuff I know we are made of (and a nod to NASA's Mars landing today).   When you speak of honoring the spiritual being inside ourselves, I have decided now I will be imagining the light of a million stars I know came before me and make up who I am :)   Also, I've realized (finally) there are a lot of people like me out there who can't transition from downward dog to a lunge smoothly or whatever pose we are trying to master, and that if I have to do it with blocks or even in 2 or 3 steps instead of one...that's frickin okay.   If I never get to where I can do a certain move, who cares, I'll do the best I can or a modification that works for me.    I really did surrender today and I didn't force a single thing... and you know what?  I did everything you asked and it wasn't a struggle (not to say it was easy...lol).   Sure, I had to put my other foot down when doing a side plank, but I did it!  If I don't ever get comfortable not putting that second foot down....I don't care anymore (doesnt mean i wont keep trying, though).  I do me, not you or anyone else.  I'm so naturally competitive but today I surrendered that!  Wow...best yoga practice yet for me.  I hope I can keep up this feeling but for today I really did surrender and let go...and believe me...that's one of the hardest things in the world for me to do.    I"m proud of me!  I just wish I could have figured this out before practice #78!!!!!  lol.

Adriene,

Today, it clicked. It clicked before this practice even started. While I've always been an active/athletic person, and I've dabbled in yoga for years, and I started to practice with you more regularly starting this August, but this TRUE journey has been my first-ever (!) commitment to setting intentions and practicing daily. Syncing up with my breath, clearing my head, connecting--all of that is the hard work, and I find myself now getting on my mat and feeling completely open: no hesitations or expectations, no thinking about the poses, just being and doing.  Thank you so much for being such a great teacher! TRUE has started to change my life, and I am thrilled to continue!
